
# 5.2. Layout Inheritance and Block Architecture

## 1. The DRY Principle in Django Templates
The **DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)** principle is a core philosophy of Django development. Standard web layouts often share common elements like headers, footers, meta tags, and navigation bars on every page. 

Rather than copying and pasting this boilerplate HTML into each individual file, Django templates use **Layout Inheritance** to share a single base layout.

```mermaid
graph TD
    Parent[base.html - Parent Layout] -->|Inherits Structure| Child[dashboard.html - Child Layout]
    Parent -->|Inherits Structure| Detail[detail.html - Child Layout]
    
    subgraph "Parent Layout Blocks"
        ParentBlockTitle[block title]
        ParentBlockContent[block content]
    end
    
    subgraph "Child Layout Overrides"
        ChildBlockTitle[Overriding block title]
        ChildBlockContent[Overriding block content]
    end

    ParentBlockTitle -.-> ChildBlockTitle
    ParentBlockContent -.-> ChildBlockContent
```

## 2. Setting Up Layout Inheritance

### Step 1: Create the Parent Template (`base.html`)
The parent template defines the shared HTML layout structure. It uses `{% block <name> %}` tags to mark dynamic regions that child templates can override.
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>{% block title %}Medical Management Portal{% endblock %}</title>
</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <nav>
            <a href="/">Dashboard</a> | <a href="/patients/">Patient Lists</a>
        </nav>
    </header>

    <main class="container">
        <!-- Dynamic content region to be populated by child templates -->
        {% block content %}
            <p>Default content placeholder.</p>
        {% endblock %}
    </main>

    <footer>
        <p>&copy; 2026 Enterprise Medical Systems Inc.</p>
    </footer>
</body>
</html>
```

### Step 2: Create a Child Template (`dashboard.html`)
The child template uses the `{% extends %}` tag to inherit from the parent layout. It then overrides specific blocks with page-specific content.
```html
<!-- Extends MUST be the first template tag in the file -->
{% extends "base.html" %}

<!-- Override the page title -->
{% block title %}Dashboard Overview - Clinical Portal{% endblock %}

<!-- Override the body content -->
{% block content %}
    <h1>Welcome to the Clinical Dashboard</h1>
    <p>Operational status: Normal.</p>
{% endblock %}
```

## 3. Reusable Subcomponents Using `include`
While `extends` is used to inherit complete page structures, the `{% include %}` tag is used to embed smaller, reusable HTML fragments (like badges, charts, or alert boxes) inside other templates.

### Example: Navigation Card Fragment (`_patient_card.html`)
```html
<div class="patient-card">
    <h3>{{ patient.nom }}</h3>
    <p>Email: {{ patient.email }}</p>
</div>
```

### Including the Fragment in a Dashboard Template
```html
<div class="patients-grid">
    {% for patient in patients %}
        <!-- Inject the partial layout template into this section -->
        {% include "partials/_patient_card.html" with patient=patient %}
    {% endfor %}
</div>